description: There's some ants eating this ladybug! What kind are they?

Observed on a sidewalk close to a large anthill. The anthill itself was interwoven with grass. The purpose of the ants moving frantically outside the hill was unclear, as they did not appear to be carrying anything. While 10-15 active ants were observed, there are likely thousands residing in the closest anthill and others nearby. The temperature was 79 degrees and the anthills were observed in direct sunlight.
A worker atop its hill. Next to a sidewalk.
Found in a small field in a neighborhood in Tampa. The ants were exiting an ant hill after a rain shower. Warm, humid weather.
I was walking around the neighborhood park and saw these

The organism was found outside on a sidewalk in 85 degrees Fahrenheit and sunny with some clouds. It has a dark red body and similar to other ants. However, the difference in body color makes it this type of ant according to: http://entoweb.okstate.edu/ddd/insects/rifa.htm
It was approximately 89 degrees. I found these on a concrete path devouring some sort of food. This is a protostome.

This ant is red in color and has a large frame, with an even larger abdomen compared to other ants. I found this ant near some wooden park benches and tables where people tend to sit and have lunch while at the park. This ant probably lives near or in these wooden structures and makes the most out of any fallen lunch leftovers. 
Collins, Laura. “Solenopsis Invicta Buren .” Red Imported Fire Ant - Solenopsis Invicta, 2001, entnemdept.ufl.edu/creatures/urban/ants/red_imported_fire_ant.htm.
10x magnification with Bausch & Lomb Hastings Triplet.

Visual Description: Brown to dark brown color, the head, and the abdomen are of similar size, their bodies are hairless and smooth. their size can be estimated to be about 1/8 of an inch in length. 

defining characteristics: this organism is a Protostome, due to it having an exoskeleton and being bilaterally symmetrical. 

Habitat: This species is common in states like Arizona, California, Illinois, Maryland, and Florida. This specific ant was observed in Sorbonne Loop, Seffner right outside of its colony in a grassland. 

reference: https://urbanentomology.tamu.edu/urban-pests/ants/argentine/
Ouch if you don't watch your feet they are everywhere out here
Immediate activity from small ants when mound was disturbed
Predation on some sort of lep larvae
